 Image might initialize `RamUsageEstimator` when creating the image. Consequently, the runtime tests wouldn't execute that initializer. However, the coverage report is generated on the JVM. If everything is done at build time, there shouldn't be any issues. I might need to import `RamUsageEstimator`.\\\"}]}\"}, {\"type\": \"toolCall\", \"id\": \"call_8BpskhZKfqtR8MaDU2eAez40|fc_0ae08bc83715e2ff0169f42ea8c1448194b4edc1d9c9e06a7e\", \"name\": \"read\", \"arguments\": {\"path\": \"/home/vjovanov/c/forge/forge2/graalvm-reachability-metadata/forge/local_repositories/source_context/org.apache.lucene/lucene-core/4.10.4/main/extracted/org/apache/lucene/util/RamUsageEstimator.java\", \"offset\": 461, \"limit\": 80}}], \"api\": \"openai-responses\", \"provider\": \"OCA\", \"model\": \"gpt-5.5\", \"usage\": {\"input\": 2809, \"output\": 1249, \"cacheRead\": 15872, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"totalTokens\": 19930, \"cost\": {\"input\": 0, \"output\": 0, \"cacheRead\": 0, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"total\": 0}}, \"stopReason\": \"toolUse\", \"timestamp\": 1777610392126, \"responseId\": \"resp_0ae08bc83715e2ff0169f42e9879888194bd82a0f7582eb4c7\"}}\n1240:[tool-exec] start id=call_8BpskhZKfqtR8MaDU2eAez40|fc_0ae08bc83715e2ff0169f42ea8c1448194b4edc1d9c9e06a7e name=read args={\"path\": \"/home/vjovanov/c/forge/forge2/graalvm-reachability-metadata/forge/local_repositories/source_context/org.apache.lucene/lucene-core/4.10.4/main/extracted/org/apache/lucene/util/RamUsageEstimator.java\", \"offset\": 461, \"limit\": 80}\n1278:[recv] {\"type\": \"turn_end\", \"message\": {\"role\": \"assistant\", \"content\": [{\"type\": \"thinking\", \"thinking\": \"**Considering naming conventions and testing**\\n\\nI need to figure out a naming convention for the package coordinate and create it under the existing `org_apache_lucene.lucene_core` package. Testing should be outside the library package, and I need to keep in mind not to use reflection directly. The inner test class fields are fine, especially since `RamUsageEstimator` uses reflection. I'll ensure there's no `getDeclaredFields` in my tests and focus on assertions with JUnit or AssertJ. I also need to consider how the user-code filter works regarding reflection in test classes.\\n\\n**Evaluating reflection and metadata issues**\\n\\nI’m considering whether the filter is for conditional configurations when the caller is the library. It may include target classes. However, if the metadata is empty, maybe the tests haven’t run before. This workflow likely runs coverage, not a full native build. The issue arises because, in Native Image, calling `Class.getDeclaredFields()` on a test class needs the reflection metadata. I wonder if the agent needs to be running before native compilation to generate the necessary config effectively. It's safest to rely on JVM if there are uncertainties with field metadata in Native Image.\\n\\n**Assessing test execution and initialization**\\n\\nI’m thinking that if tests run in native mode after the agent, it could be fine. But there's a potential issue: the static initializer (clinit) may occur before the agent runs. If the class gets initialized at build time, then the Native Image might initialize `RamUsageEstimator` when creating the image. Consequently, the runtime tests wouldn't execute that initializer. However, the coverage report is generated on the JVM. If everything is done at build time, there shouldn't be any issues. I might need to import `RamUsageEstimator`.\", \"thinkingSignature\": \"{\\\"id\\\":\\\"rs_0ae08bc83715e2ff0169f42e9908848194bcf90ff5336827bd\\\",\\\"type\\\":\\\"reasoning\\\",\\\"encrypted_content\\\":\\\"gAAAAABp9C6ocZkqFleI2PjQbV9wrSaUISO-UC6DWAPDE3x57Ke65XgxsVGmZGKojIWlOZ2qMSqU6FRO1FWZeN7nlQcRxJ-1Ee-RPAQmHYZKYvfDd3lzzkjfcZaHXEHeboD6hQRMuwm18DBk-2CxUCb2AsQac6sfaP7SpPkn1Ea9-KRtgSd9PpXklGhh48GAoLuaPr7pCDOQ-0KCvIFKK09vvi10YAOZ1sROFCJ_ogpRThWOergjeoiLByxgL1EKOHmW3gvdcIBhCybsYgh3ghm8ZrLZ0P1Ng2TTmjlTfpQybY_nx-yT9rCWD_KxBF3p3rLbxNkxZg95zJzhrfaGcNiMdjmNsbpAV5zlaWX